text: Summary.  Drug-induced  myelotoxicity  is  usually  the  dose-limiting  factor  of  treatment  of  malignant  tumors  with  cytostatic drugs.  Suppression  of in vitro  myelopoie-  sis  (CFU-GM)  by  cytostatics  may  be  a  suitable  model  reflecting the in vivo situation.  Thus the inhibitory effects  of  the  anthracyclines  doxorubicin,  theprubicin,  idarubi-  cin  and  cytorhodin S  on  CFU-GM  were  compared.  Nor-  mal  human  bone  marrow  cells were  incubated  with  these  drugs  for one hour  and  alternatively,  for the whole culture  period.  For  each  substance  and  each  incubation  time  a  dose-response  curve  was  established  and  the  Ds0  deter-  mined.  As  certain  calcium  antagonists  can  increase  the  toxicity of some cytostatic drugs in various tumor  models,  the  effect  of  the  addition  of  verapamil  (2  pM)  was  also  investigated.  It could be shown,  that  the myelotoxicity on  CFU-GM  of the  drugs mentioned above was not increased  after  short-term  or  permanent  exposure  to  this  calcium  antagonist.  Key words:  Anthracyclines  -  Verapamil  -  Bone marrow  progenitors

Resistance  of tumor  cells to  anthracycline  cytostatics can  at  least  partially  be  overcome  by  the  design  of  possibly  non  cross-resistant  derivatives  [13] or,  as  could  be  shown  in  various  tumor  models  [11, 15]  and  possibly  in  clinical  situations  [3]  by  the  combination  of  anthracyclines  with  calcium antagonists,  usually verapamil.  The possible gain  of such combinations,  i.e.  improved tumor  cell kill,  could  be  outweighed  however  if  side-effects  of  treatment  in-  creased  concomitantly. Since  the  myelotoxicity of cytostatic drugs  seems to  be  at  least  par-  tially  caused  by their  effect  on  committed  hematopoietic  progenitors  of  the  granulocyte/monocyte lineage  (CFU-  GM)  [8],  analysis  of  the  influence  of  the  verapamil/  anthracycline  combination  on  CFU-GM  may  be  predic-  tive  for  the  in  vivo  situation.  Since  published  data  have  until  now  only  described  the  effect  of  verapamil  on  the  toxicity  of  doxorubicin  to  CFU-GM  [4, 14, 16]  and  since  the  influence  of  verapamil  on  cellular  accumulation  is  not  uniform  for  all  anthracycline  derivatives  [7],  we  now  extend  these  studies  to  the  newer  anthracyclines  4-de-  methoxydaunorubicin,  4'-(R)-0-tetrahydropyranyl-adria-  mycin  and  cytorhodin  S.

Resistance  of tumor  cells to  commonly employed anthra-  cyclines  such  as  doxorubicin  has  led  to  the  development  of  newer  anthracycline  derivatives  with  little  or  no  cross  resistance in in vitro tumor models  6,  13.  Our  data  show  that,  in  comparison to  their  toxicity towards  mammalian  tumor  cell  lines  6,  the  newer  anthracycline  derivatives  idarubicin  and  theprubicin  exhibit  a  remarkably  similar  toxicity  towards  normal  myeloid  bone  marrow  progeni-  tors  (CFU-GM)  after  short-term  exposure.  Preliminary  results  (Behringwerke  AG,  product  information)  suggest  that  the  same  also  holds  true  for  the  new  tetraglycosidic  derivative  cytorhodin S.  While  the  anthracycline  concen-  trations  necessary to inhibit  colony growth by 50%  show-  ed  pronounced  differences  after  1 h  of  preincubation,  these  differences  seemed  to  level  off with  increased  dura-  tion  of  drug  exposure.  As  differences  in  uptake  kinetics  for  doxorubicin  and  daunorubicin  were  recently  demon-  strated  for  crude  human  bone  marrow  12,  we  speculate  that  similar  mechanisms  may be responsible  for the  find-  ings  obtained  with  the  derivatives  employed in  our  study  and the  CFU-GM subpopulation  of bone marrow cells  as  well. We  therefore  examined  the  in-  fluence  of  verapamil  on  their  in  vitro  haematopoietic  toxicity.  Our  data  show  that  these  anthracyclines  behave  in the  same  way as  doxorubicin with  no  increase of toxic-  ity  towards  CFU-GM  independent  of  the  duration  of  drug  exposure.  As  toxicity  to  bone  marrow  progenitors  may  at  least  partially  be  predictive  for  bone  marrow  toxicity observed in vivo, these  findings suggest that  com-  binations  of  the  anthracycline  derivatives  idarubicin,  theprubicin  and  cytorhodin  S  with  verapamil  may  be  clinically  feasible.  10.
